snippet.textDisplay: “21 Years” is a song I wrote about the recent passing of my firstborn son, Truett Foster McKeehan. I loved him with all my heart. Until something in life hits you this hard, you never know how you will handle it. I am thankful that I have been surrounded by love, starting with God’s and extending to community near and far that have walked with us and carried us every day. Writing this song felt like an honest confession of the questions, pain, anger, doubt, mercy and promise that describes the journey I’m probably only beginning. The rest is yet to come. One thing I know is that I am not alone. God didn’t promise us a life of no pain or even tragic death, but He did promise He would never leave us or forsake us. And I’m holding dearly to that promise for my son as well as myself.

snippet.textDisplay:
My beautiful first born took his life at the age of 22. Following in his dad's footsteps. Even though he never knew the story of his dad's death, the ending was terrifyingly similar. Jesus took me through it all... the anger, pain, depression and bone crushing guilt.
At some point you stop asking why? And let go of the "What if" and you just be still and Know. Then you begin to live again. There is so much comfort in the scriptures. So much Love in the Lord. Pray for those with mental illness and take time to listen to those in your life. John 10:28 helped me a lot to know that my son is with Jesus b/c Justin was saved. And no man (not even himself) can pluck him from God's mighty hand.
Thank you for this song, it is a gift of worship, in a dark storm.
Keep on Praising! For He is Worthy💖

snippet.textDisplay: You are a gift to the world that God created to help the helpless and the hopeless. Your beautiful and powerful songs were some of the songs I sung while being verbally abused by my ex husband. I would lay on the ground in tears,  hearing his screaming in the background being faded by my weary voice softly sing your lyrics which gave me strength and at the same time a sense of peace and even hope. Ive now gone through my journey to heal my heart and mind and am thriving by the grace of God🙌 We love you Toby, my wonderful brother in Christ. After hearing you for years through my CDs and on the radio, I had the honor of seeing you perform at Rock the Universe last year. It was such a monumental, precious and magical moment for me. Thank you from the bottom of my heart for selflessly and lovingly serving our Lord through your music. I know that Truett is very proud of his daddy. You will hold him  again just like I will hold my beautiful baby girl again. God bless you hun, keep touching lives. You will get many hugs and thank yous when you get to Heaven

snippet.textDisplay: It literally shatters me to see Tru in pictures/videos in the end. It breaks me in ways I can't describe. I cannot imagine what it does to his family, if this is how powerful a reaction I have to it.  I know we shouldn't be sad b/c to be absent from the body, is to be present w/the Lord, but man does it hurt so much. God please be with Tru's family & friends. Shield them from the agonizing pain & sadness & grief that will bring them to their knees & rip open every pore in their body to weep the loss of someone so precious. You know what it's like to lose your Son & see Him suffer, so you know the pain, you know the earth shattering bereavement & emptiness. Fill the void w/the Holy Spirit's protection from the pain & sting. Heal their scars, cover their wounds in life sustaining salve that stops the bleed of pain, anger, doubt, regret, guilt, what if's & immense suffering from the absent spot once filled in their life by this child. Tru was so beautiful, so full of life, so loved, so supported, so sacred to his family. Provide them the peace & trust that only you can provide. Give them signs, give them protection, give them evidence of your soverignity in all this. Let them know you have & will cover their open wounds. Amen

snippet.textDisplay: My mum passed away 2 and a half years ago. She was healthy at 56 years. I still remember that day I found out she had collapsed and was in a coma. Incredible song. The sudden deaths hurt so bad. Can't help but make me think of my cousin who was like a sister to me that was killed in a car wreck 3 years ago this May. She would be 24 years old today.




I think about her all the time...God has her in heaven, but I have her in my heart. Thank you Toby, for telling your story and making the hurt a little easier to feel.

snippet.textDisplay:
A very nice song, music and lyrics. It does what it's designed to do, make you feel good about the deceased and where they're spending eternity. The sad fact is that Toby's son was a prodical (that never turned back) that died in rebellion against God. I have an adult daughter that's about the same age as Toby's son Truett, who's also in rebellion against God. As painful as it is, though it might sound harsh, if she or any of us die in fornication, overdose of drugs, suicide, adultery, idolators, liars, thieves extortioners, covetous, etc. etc. we're not getting into heaven. Jesus is either our Savior or our Righteous Judge. According to Hebrews 5:9 he's the author of salvation for those who obey him. According to 1st Corinthians 6:9-11, Romans 1 , Galatians 5, Revelation 21 there are certain criteria for making it into heaven. It's a narrow road to heaven few find Jesus said. In conclusion, It's a beautiful song, but God forbid we give anyone license to sin and false hope that they'll go to heaven while abiding in what God hates (SIN). John 3:36 (KJV)
He that believeth on the Son hath everlasting life: and he that believeth not the Son shall not see life; but the wrath of God abideth on him.
God bless you and comfort you all. 🙏

snippet.textDisplay:
I cannot begin to fathom the extent of the pain this family is experiencing. I only know pain from our loss....
People told me we needed to "get over" losing my 29 year old brother....
You never get over it....You learn to live with part of your heart amputated....
Know that I am praying for this family....and did in the days past, now, and for the days ahead.
For the folks getting irritated at the dislikes....be patient. Perhaps those people have not experienced such a sudden loss and cannot comprehend. For them to be able to do so would mean they, too, would have grieved as deeply....
Don't get irritated with them....pity them for their lack of sensitivity.
